Quarterly Crypto Fundraising Review: Q3 2024

Andrew Dyer

Oct 16, 2024   21 min read

Key Insights

  • Overall deal announcement activity has ticked down QoQ in Q3, but the total dollar value raised is in-line with the past three quarters at almost $4 billion.
  • DeFi and A.I. remain the primary focus for venture funds as NFT, gaming, and metaverse projects lose some steam versus prior quarters.
  • A.I. and DePIN sectors have both grown tremendously in terms of dollar value raised versus a year ago. Meanwhile, the DeSci sector saw large increases in number of rounds versus last quarter.
  • While the US still dominates the crypto venture scene, investor entities in the APAC region are growing in influence and participation across rounds. Eastern entities tend to invest more in games, game studios, and metaverse-adjacent projects.
  • VC theses this quarter focused on how blockchains can democratize access to A.I. models, how DePIN can incentivize useful infrastructure building, and even how financial nihilism impacts consumer apps.

Quarterly Overview

While venture fundraising activity has picked up since the 2023 lows, we have yet to eclipse the frothy conditions and rampant fundraising of the last bull market. If anything, Q3 of this year was a bit muted compared to the past two quarters. The value raised by protocols and startups in the space was around $3.8 billion. This amount is in-line with the past year, but with about 35% fewer funding rounds.

Investor participation, as measured by the number of unique investors per quarter, had been trending up, but is still around 40% off its 2022 high. Looking at more granular monthly data, we can see venture funding and overall activity are largely reactive to liquid market prices:

The high correlation between these series is visually evident, but even more so when we lag total crypto market capitalization by a few months. The correlation between the three series jumps from around .74 to .8 with a lag of one to two months. Venture funding announcements and overall risk appetite mostly follow the price in public markets on a multi-month lag; research from AngelList says that this lag could be as long as nine to eighteen months for VC investments. They note that even as public markets decline, ongoing deal negotiations and committed capital can maintain VC activity levels for some time before slowing (and vice versa). Its no surprise then that TOTAL bottomed more than six months before the resumption of announcements, which themselves are lagged from actual raises.

We can imagine that funding activity will see another surge if crypto majors start breaking out above prior cycle highs. However, that activity is momentum-driven is not too surprising, nor the most useful insight that we can draw from Messaris vast fundraising data. For the investors that remained in the space after a grueling bear market, where are they now focused, and where is the money flowing?

The Evolution of Sector Allocation

Some of the largest protocols by FDV by the end of the bull market in 2021-2022 were in the gaming, metaverse, and NFT sectors. Gaming platforms like The SandBox and Gala hit $5-6 billion in FDV despite limited user adoption, while OpenSea at one point raised at a $13 billion valuation. Naturally, venture funding continued flowing into these sectors, seeking similar outsized returns and valuations. As new funds and the NFT market activity dried up, venture allocations once again shifted back to primarily DeFi investments.

DeFi is a fairly broad tag in the Messari taxonomy and includes liquid staking, DEXs, yield aggregators, payment solutions, and other forms of marketplaces. Within DeFi, Lending, Yield Services, and RWA featured most frequently this quarter.

The tag with the greatest QoQ increase was Healthcare. These rounds were generally a part of the DeSci movement, which uses crypto rails to make scientific research and collaboration more transparent, accessible, and incentivized. They include protocols and companies like Aminochain, Universal Health Token, and BIO protocol. Messari covered the promise and aspiration of the DeSci movement in a recent Mainnet panel.

Among the tags that saw the largest QoQ decrease, Gambling was a notable loser, going from 11 to 1 round in Q3. Its possible that a combination of Pump.fun and Moonshot are fulfilling the crowds need for speculation, making web3 imitations of traditional casinos less attractive to venture firms.

The Largest Raises

Outside of Celestias recent $100 million OTC token sale, we had large raises in the decentralized AI space, with Sentient and Ceti raising $85 and $60 million, respectively. The increasing allocation to the crypto-AI intersection will likely be a recurring theme this quarter.

While we noted NFT volumes have fallen off significantly, NFTs and the broader gaming and metaverse sectors are still alive. ID Planet, a Metaverse hub consisting of mobile games, an NFT marketplace, and social apps, raised $80 million in Series B funding this quarter. Tune.fm is pushing on the music collectibles (and artist royalties) front, and Kain Warwicks new DeFi platform Infinex even raised its $65 million in funding through Patron NFTs.

In fact, if we divide our ~600 rounds into quintiles, we see that AI is the most frequent tag among the largest disclosed raises.

While there were fewer total number of AI rounds this quarter compared to the last two - perhaps as a result of slower overall activity - the amount raised in AI rounds has increased by more than 340% YoY to around $213 million. As we run through the notable rounds of this quarter, we are reminded of a recent tweet from Frictionless Capitals Logan Jastremski:

Bittensor - an ecosystem of specialized AI/ML subnets - has surged from $1.6 billion in market capitalization at the beginning of this year to around $4.7 billion today. While Messari has discussed potential issues with Bittensors current economic design, its size is a testament to market demand in this vertical. Artificial intelligence as a sector within crypto is still only around $30 billion, a mere sub-2% of total crypto market capitalization. Its likely for that percentage to grow significantly over the next year, given continued venture activity in the sector.

Outside of AI, DePIN investments have also increased significantly. Compared to a year ago this quarter, total capital raised from DePIN rounds shot up an astounding 691% to around $69 million (based on tagged rounds with disclosed amounts raised).

Biggest Gainers and Losers

Pencils Protocol is the only round from this quarter that raised at a higher (disclosed) post-money valuation, a 195% increase from their previous round at around $27 million. Pencils is a Scroll-native yield aggregator, auction, and farming platform with $410 million in TVL. Pencils has likely been benefiting from $SCRs upcoming airdrop, which will be claimable on October 22, 2024.

There were no down rounds in any of the raises this quarter.

Geographical Trends

The US still dominates the crypto venture scene with 304 rounds represented this quarter. Singapore, Hong Kong, and the UK are also becoming early-stage crypto hubs as well. The UAE has seen the greatest growth in the number of rounds YoY, which makes sense as it continues to cater to high-net worth individuals with crypto-friendly tax laws. Japan had the greatest QoQ increase in the number of deals but from a relatively small base. Most firms across the world invested in fewer rounds versus last quarter.

Are there any notable trends across firms based on where they are headquartered? Sorted by sector:

Funds in Asia generally deploy to more gaming rounds on average, while Europe and the US have been more focused on Exchanges. The Asia Pacific region has taken the lead in crypto game development, with 40% of developers based in the region, according to Game7 Research. South Korea and Japan have also seen a rapid rise in crypto game development teams as a percentage of the global total.

Accelerator Spotlight

Accelerator programs do small initial funding rounds and help startups with token design, product design, infrastructure, security, marketing, and future fundraising. They are an integral part of this budding industry and usually represent around 20-30% of the total number of deals per quarter (~23% for Q3 2024). Top programs include a16zs Crypto Startup School (CSX), Beacon, One Piece Labs, and Alliance DAO. Where have accelerator programs been investing, and how has this changed over the quarters?

The most popular sectors for Accelerator investments have generally been Exchanges and Gaming. This quarter Exchange edged out as the winner for the most number of Accelerator deals. The sector this quarter tilted towards new DEXs like Avantis on Base, Regenerative.fi on Celo, and Quenta on Iotex. Marketplaces for different types of services and assets were also popular: Fermah functions as a marketplace for ZK proofs, Fandora allows users to invest in content IP, and alt.DRX manages a platform for fractional, tokenized real estate investing. New DeFi protocols in accelerator programs this quarter usually have a unique spin on the typical primitives, either involving RWAs, DePIN, or new types of tokenized assets.

But exchanges, marketplaces, and DeFi are fairly broad sectors. If we drill down into tags (which may have some overlap), AI emerges as a strong runner-up.

Some of the more prolific accelerator programs take in numerous AI startups as part of their regular cohorts. The AI x Crypto intersection spans multiple verticals, including decentralized compute networks, AI agents, coordination + incentivization platforms, and applications where underlying AI models are utilized for some consumer usage. One way crypto rails might aid the democratization of AI is through the decentralization of resources, which may lead to lower inference costs for consumers and businesses.

Accelerator startup Exo Labss open-source architecture allows consumer devices (like two MacBook Pros) to run AI clusters at home. Decentralized inference may be particularly useful for privacy and model verification purposes. Exos mission has garnered the attention of both hyperscalers like Meta and users on Github alike.

Prolific Investors and Their Theses

Animoca Brands

Excluding accelerator rounds, we can see the most prolific venture backer this quarter was Animoca Brands. Animoca is one of the most prominent players in the blockchain, gaming, and digital entertainment space. Its venture arm focuses mostly on gaming and metaverse projects, with almost 50% of its Q3 rounds involved in gaming and NFTs. The biggest raise Animoca was involved in gaming this quarter was in E-PAL, a gaming and social companion platform. Users can pay popular Epals (streamers and companion players) to play popular games like Fortnite or Overwatch with them. However, as with many funding rounds this quarter, even when the primary category of the recipient project is a particular sector, there is often AI involved secondarily. This round is primarily allocated to develop Balance, which is E-PALs new AI-powered blockchain experience platform - the project's next iteration.

Balance aims to be a one-stop shop for web2 and web3 gamers, providing both AI and human companion players, its own first-party games, NFT launchpads and marketplaces, Epal fan tokens, and an entire infrastructure layer. Six of Animocas other fundraising events this quarter also involved AI in one form or another. Even for a firm that focuses on gaming and social platforms, AI is becoming a central part of any venture firms thesis on the future of their sector. Back in 2023, Animoca Founder, Yat Siu told Financial News London:

If we think about AIs transacting with each other as autonomous beings in the future, what currency they will transact in, it has to be crypto. In the future, 70-80% of transactions will happen through autonomous AI agents and the decentralized nature of crypto makes it a perfect match.

NFTs and mechanisms for ownership in a digital, social era are important for credit attribution and value flowing to content creators. As AI-generated content proliferates the web, this concept may become more important. Siu explained this trend earlier this year:

Robot Ventures

While Animoca is heavily focused on gaming, NFTs, and social (with some overlaps with AI), Robot Ventures (RV) is almost exclusively focused on DeFi and infrastructure. Around 20% of Robot Ventures rounds were involved in liquid staking or staking, such as investments in Lombard, Ion Protocol, Level, and Eigenpie. They also invested in ZK protocols like Pi Squared, zkME, and Zircuit. However, like Animoca, RV was still compelled to participate in an AI round. The large seed round ($85 million) for Sentient - the open platform for AGI development - made quite the splash in the news earlier this summer.

Other large rounds RV participated in were for Morpho Labs, the permissionless lending protocol that has seen a lot of traction since its launch of Morpho Blue earlier this year. Morpho is one protocol that may benefit from the increasing attractiveness of onchain yields in a declining interest rate environment.

RV participated in Huma Finances large raise of $38 million. Huma aims to create a payment financing (PayFi) network through blockchain rails and stablecoins. The protocol recently merged with Arf, a liquidity solution platform for cross-border payments. The combined entities are projected to hit $10 billion in payments-financing transactions next year, highlighting a massive use case of stablecoins like USDC to create more efficiency in the payments space.

Lastly, RV participated in two notable DePIN rounds, one for DAWN, the decentralized broadband protocol, and Pipe Network, a permissionless content delivery network on Solana. As projects like Helium and GEODNET become emblematic of how crypto incentives can solve real-world problems, investor interest in the DeWI, DeGEN, and other DePIN subsectors is likely to continue.

RV heads Robert Leshner (Compound founder) and Tarun Chitra both have separate projects they are building alongside their work at RV. Leshner is the CEO of Superstate, an RWA platform, and Chitra is the CEO of Gauntlet, which helps protocols with risk and treasury management. Interviews with Leshner and Chitra indicate their bullishness on ZK technology:

When Chitra was asked if he sees any interesting financial primitives he thought would become more and more important:

I mean, in general, I think re-staking comes under that. But things that let you not know what network you're on, but give you the same security guarantees of that network; re-staking is one version of that, aggregation stuff that people are doing and ZK-land is one version of that. I think that's the key to making the UX of the multi-chain world feel anywhere near as good as something like Solana.

One thesis Chitra mentioned was about financial nihilism, which is probably not reflected in RV investments, but is interesting nonetheless:

Binance Labs

Binance Labs (BL) - recently separated from Binance the exchange - came in third by the number of rounds this quarter. BL has historically invested across all verticals in the crypto space, in both Accelerator and normal seed rounds. However, this quarter saw an almost equal amount of deals in the AI and DeFi tags. BLs AI investments this quarter include Aggregata with its GPT-to-earn model, MyShell with its unique character AI chatbots and agents, Sahara AI with its layered AI blockchain platform, and Pentagon Games (also backed by Animoca) with its AI-driven gaming platform. BLs Max Coniglios recently commented on the AI x Crypto intersection that is driving a lot of his firms recent investments:

Outside of AI, BL has also been supportive of the budding BTC ecosystem, with recent investments in Corn, a yield network on Bitcoin, and Hemi Labs, a modular network for scaling both Bitcoin and Ethereum. Binances ongoing support of new protocols on Bitcoin makes sense, given their leaderships views on it versus the rest of the market. BLs Alex Odagiu explains:

Bitcoins dominant position in the market is deeply rooted in its status as the first cryptocurrency, which institutional investors often view as a simpler, more familiar, and less risky asset compared to Ethereum and altcoins. Bitcoins narrative as a store of value, often referred to as digital gold, aligns with traditional investment strategies, making it a natural entry point for institutions new to the crypto space.

On the DeFi side, BL also invested in Solayer, which aims to extend Solanas security at the base layer to its apps through restaking. They made another restaking-related investment in EigenExplorer, a platform that provides data APIs to quickly access data about the EigenLayer ecosystem.

Venture Whales and their Theses

a16z Crypto

A16zs six rounds in Q3 spanned various verticals, with two investments in gaming (one in Balance, mentioned earlier), and one in DePIN, lending, IP infrastructure, and DeSci. While the firm did not make any explicit AI investments, they do view their investment in Story Protocol as a bet on AI changing the economic covenant between creators and platforms:

As we mentioned in our August DePIN update, decentralized energy or DeGEN is a budding subsector within DePIN that aims to use crypto rails to optimize physical energy infrastructure. Guy Wuollet and Ali Yahya of a16z mention Daylights potential to efficiently deploy distributed energy resources (DERs):

DERs are often used to reduce load on the electrical grid, or even supply power to the grid, during times of peak demand. Their source is usually an individual household or business that has no clear incentive to provide that support when its needed. Solving this collective action problem could be invaluable for our energy grid.

A16zs investments in games and game studios are also aligned with the Read, Write, Own ethos of empowering creators. Moku, a web3 games publisher and launchpad on Ronin has a large creator program of over 3000 members. The small round will be used to enable their community of gamers to publish their own games on the platform. A16z is excited about web gaming and social gaming more broadly, as Joshua Lu notes:

In recent years, indie publishing platform itch.iowhich hosts over 400,000 browser-based gameshas shown theres still an audience for web games. After the mega-hit web game Wordle took the world by storm in 2021 and 2022, the New York Times acquired it and began touting the success of its expanding games empire. Theres proven demand for web games, if only a serious, gaming-focused company can solve the distribution challenge and connect devs with the right audience.

Another notable trend in the raises this quarter among games and game studios was many of them launching on Ronin, which we covered recently here.

Pantera Capital

Panteras eight rounds this quarter were tilted towards AI (Sentient, Sahara, and Gradient Network) and gaming (GAMEE and NPC Labs). A common theme behind many of these AI investments has been the need to democratize access to powerful models, maintain user privacy, and ensure AI progress is transparent. From Panteras announcements on Sahara and Sentient, respectively:

We believe that fair access to AIs benefits and proper compensation for all contributors are crucial. Blockchain technology offers a unique solution to democratize AI development and usage, ensuring that these values are upheld. Additionally, as demand grows for AI agents customized to proprietary data, scalable infrastructure that prioritizes user privacy and ownership will become increasingly essential.

Current AI ownership models either restrict access and innovation through closed systems or lack incentives through open models. We believe there is a critical need for a decentralized approach that maintains robust security, promotes innovation, and ensures fair economic incentives.

Another trend among rounds this quarter within gaming was the number of investments in Telegram mini-apps and their studios. GAMEE is a mobile gaming platform (and a subsidiary of Animoca Brands) that is using the TON ecosystem to enhance its distribution to a wider audience. Pantera succinctly expressed its conviction in the TON onboarding thesis earlier this year:

99.999% of blockchain projects are a tech idea trying to create a community from nothing. According to CoinMarketCap there are more than 23,000 cryptocurrencies. Thats a hard road for most. Telegram is a community integrating blockchain technology. Thats just got to be easier.

Multicoin Capital

Multicoins six Q3 investments were mostly focused in the DePIN sector. We mentioned Pipe Network briefly, but Kyle Samani explains his thesis on decentralized content delivery networks:

A decentralized CDN (dCDN), built on crypto rails, has always been an obvious opportunity. Theoretically, a dCDN should be able to offer lower latency and more redundancy at lower cost due to a structural cost arbitrage on dramatically underutilized upload bandwidth

CDNs are naturally performance sensitive applications. With the right orchestration, a dCDN should be able to outcompete a centralized CDN (cCDN). However, building the orchestration layer to support a permissionless environment is hard and net new. Building a dCDN requires a team with deep domain knowledge. We believe we have found the right team, helmed by David Rhodus, founder and CEO. David boasts a 20-year professional career in streaming media and big data.

Multicoins investment in Fuse, a London-based energy startup, also works with the DERs we mentioned earlier. Shayon Sengupta and Tushar Jain explained how decentralized rails can aid in the energy coordination problem (getting local generation and consumption for higher efficiency):

Lastly, the firms investment in Gradient Network toes the line between AI and DePIN. Gradients goal is to build out a decentralized, meshed global network that allows for high-performance edge computation. Gradient Network may allow for edge-based AI inference and content delivery, lowering latency for those services to end-users. While Multicoin hasnt spoken about edge compute specifically, they are bullish on how DePIN can deliver cost-effective and localized services:

Awards Wrap-up

While Q3 announcements fell off from earlier this year, there were plenty of newsworthy rounds and raises. A.I. and DePIN continue to garner more attention from venture firms, and will likely continue to do so in the coming quarters. While DeFi and marketplace-centric rounds receded from the limelight, they still comprised the bulk of funding events. It remains to be seen if those protocols can recapture the public markets mindshare in the same way some liquid A.I. tokens have this year. As always, you can find the most granular and up-to-date fundraising data with Messari.
